{"id":"2304.14235","submitter":"Harukuni Ikeda","authors":"Harukuni Ikeda, and Yuta Kuroda","title":"Does Spontaneous Symmetry Breaking Occur in Periodically Driven\n  Low-Dimensional Non-Equilibrium Classical Systems?","comments":"7 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.soft","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In one and two dimensions, equilibrium systems with continuous degrees of\nfreedom do not show the spontaneous symmetry breaking, as the thermal\nfluctuation destroys the long-range orders. The simplest way to suppress\nfluctuations and realize the long-range orders in low-dimensional systems is\njust to consider the ground state at zero temperature. A less trivial example\nis an out-of-equilibrium system driven by periodic driving forces, instead of\nthermal agitation. If the amplitude of the driving force is sufficiently small,\nthe periodic force of frequency $\\omega_0$ only excites the eigenmode of the\neigenfrequency $\\omega_0$. Therefore, the fluctuations would be largely\nsuppressed even near the critical point, if it exists. Does this mechanism\nallows the spontaneous symmetry breaking in low dimensions? We here show that\nthe answer is positive, at least for the spherical model, which corresponds to\nthe large $n$ limit of the $O(n)$ model and allows us to analytically calculate\nthe lower critical dimension $d_l$. For that purpose, we here propose the\ndriving force inspired by the chiral active matter:\n$h(\\boldsymbol{x},t)=\\sqrt{2D}\\cos\\theta(\\boldsymbol{x},t)$, where\n$\\dot{\\theta}(\\boldsymbol{x},t)=\\omega_0+\\xi(\\boldsymbol{x},t)$, and\n$\\xi(\\boldsymbol{x},t)$ denotes the white noise. For the finite strength of the\nnoise, the model undergoes the second-order ferromagnetic phase transition at\nsome finite $D=D_c$. In particular, the lower critical dimension is $d_l=2$,\nmeaning that the ordered phase does not appear for $d\\leq d_l=2$. In the\nabsence of the noise, on the contrary, the model undergoes the ferromagnetic\nphase transition for any $d>0$, namely, $d_l=0$. Furthermore, the model for the\nconserved order parameter exhibits the hyperuniformity in the absence of the\nnoise, which has been previously reported for chiral active matter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Apr 2023 14:48:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-28"}
